<section class="calc-content">
  <h2>Understanding Appliance Power Draw</h2>
  <p>Every appliance has two critical power numbers: <strong>running watts</strong> (continuous draw during operation) and <strong>starting watts</strong> (surge required to start motors and compressors). The starting surge can be 2-5x the running watts for appliances with motors — this is critical when sizing inverters and generators.</p>
  
  <h3>BTU/hr — Why It Matters</h3>
  <p>Every watt of electricity consumed eventually becomes heat. For home AI labs and server rooms, this heat load must be removed by cooling systems. At 3.412 BTU per watt-hour, a single RTX 5090 workstation running 12 hours/day adds ~30,700 BTU of heat to your space — equivalent to running a 2.5-ton AC unit just to keep temperatures stable.</p>
  
  <h3>Off-Grid Planning</h3>
  <p>Use this database to build your load profile, then feed the results into the <a href="/off-grid-survival-estimator/">Off-Grid Survival Estimator</a> for physics-based solar, battery, and wind sizing based on your geography.</p>
</section>

